@node ProjectMenu "ANSI-Draw ... Menus - Project menu"

 @{b}New@{ub}        -  This function will erase all data in the editingbuffer and
               then insert the number of rows defined in 'Initial rows'
               under @{"GUI prefs" link PreferencesMenu}. If anything has changed in the current text
               you will be promted if you really want to continue.

 @{b}Load@{ub}       -  Loads a new ANSI-screen into the editingbuffers. If the
               current project not is saved you will be promted if you
               really want to continue loading the new one. The name of the
               file loaded will be copied to the 'Current name' menu.

 @{b}Save ANSI@{ub}  -  Saves the current project with the name defined in 'Current
               name' @{b}without@{ub} asking.

 @{b}Save ANSI as...@{ub}
               Asks the user to select under which name to save the current
               project and then saves it. The name defined will be copied to
               the menu 'Current name'.

 @{b}Save text as...@{ub}
               Asks the user to select under which name to save. It will
               save the document as pure text. All definitions of colors and
               styles will be ignored when saving. The name defined will be
               copied to the menu 'Current name'.

 @{b}Change name...@{ub}
               Opens a window with a stringgadet that allows you to redefine
               the name of the current project.

 @{b}About ANSI-draw...@{ub}
               Some information about the program.

 @{b}About user...@{ub}
               Shows who the program is registered to.

 @{b}Quit@{ub}       -  Well, what do you expect from a menufunction with the name
               quit? Ok, for those of you who don't know ... it quits the
               program! Supprised, huh?

@endnode


@node BlockMenu "ANSI-Draw ... Menus - Block menu"

 @{b}Mark@{ub}       -  This will turn on/off the marking of blocks. Marking can be
               done by turning the mark funtion on and then moving the
               cursor. The cursor can either be moved by moving it with the
               cursor keys or by klicking the left mousebutton somewhere on
               the screen. Marking can also be turned on/off by double-
               clicking the left mousebutton. The doubleclick speed is the
               same as the one used by Workbench so if you want to change it
               you have to do that in the Workbench preferences.

 @{b}Cut@{ub}        -  Erases the marked area. Only the filters that are turned on
               will be affected by this funtion. Before erasing the area,
               'Cut' will preform a 'Copy' on it.

 @{b}Copy@{ub}       -  Copies the marked area into a seperate buffer. This funtion
               is not affected by the filters, all marked information is
               copied.

 @{b}Paste@{ub}      -  Pastes the copied area from the seperate buffer onto the
               screen. It will be pasted at the cursor with the cursor
               placed in the upper left corner. If you wish to see where
               the paste will take place, use the funtion 'Show pastearea'.
               Paste is affected by the filters.

 @{b}Fill@{ub}       -  Will fill the rectangular marked area with color/text and 
               style. The colors and styles it will fill with are taken from
               the current foregroundcolor, backgroundcolor and style. The
               character that the area will be filled with is the one placed
               at the upper left corner of the marked area. If you wish not
               to fill the area with a character/color or style, simply turn
               that filter off. This funtion is affected by the filters.

 @{b}Border@{ub}     -  Draws a border inside the marked area. The border will be
               drawn with the current colors and style. The characters that
               define the border are taken from the current keypad-
               characterset. If you wish to see how this is defined just
               take a look at the predefined keypadsets. Set 2 to 5 are
               the predefined bordersets for use with the PC font. If the
               border you are about to draw is going to cross another border
               the borders will automaticly be joined together if possible.
               This funtion is affected by the filters.

 @{b}Uppercase@{ub}  -  Will turn all characters within the marked area into capital
               letters. This funtion does currently not know how to
               capitalize special characters like ĺäö etc. It capitalizes
               the ASCII-codes between 97 and 122. Uppercase is @{b}not@{ub}
               affected by the filters.


 @{b}Lowercase@{ub}  -  Will turn all characters within the marked area into lower-
               case letters. This funtion does currently not know how to
               lowercase special characters like ĺäö etc. It lowercases the
               ASCII-codes between 65 and 90. Lowercase is @{b}not@{ub} affected
               by the filters.

 @{b}Align text@{ub} -  Will align the text left/right or centered within the marked
               area. The area at the end of the block where the line was
               moved from will be erased. Only the foreground/background
               and style filters will affect this funtion which means that
               the text always will be moved.

 @{b}Line »@{ub}
   @{b}Insert@{ub}   -  This will insert an empty line at the top row of the block
               (removing the last row). The block has to be atleast two rows
               high. This function is affected by the filters.

   @{b}Remove@{ub}   -  This will remove the top row of the block (inserting an
               empty one at the bottom of the block). The block has to be
               atleast two rows high. This function is affected by the
               filters.

 @{b}Column »@{ub}
   @{b}Insert@{ub}   -  This will insert an empty column in the beginning of the
               block (removing the last). The block must be atleast two
               characters wide. This function is affected by the filters.

   @{b}Remove@{ub}   -  This will insert an empty column at the end of the block
               (removing the first). The block must be atleast two
               characters wide. This function is affected by the filters.

 @{b}Transparancy@{ub}
               This is a checkmenu. If the menu is checked it means that
               when pasting an area, the characters that are spaces with
               black background will not be pasted on the screen. This will
               result in a transparancy where the background will be seen
               through.

 @{b}Show paste area@{ub}
               Will show the area that will be affected by the paste
               function. It will show it as a flashing border around the
               area where the paste will take place.

@endnode

@node EditMenu "ANSI-Draw ... Menus - Edit menu"

 @{b}Style@{ub}       - These will alternate the checkmarks for Italic/Bold/Underline
               and reverse. The checkmarks can be seen in the @{"Edit window" link WindowMenu}.

 @{b}Filter@{ub}      - These will alternate the checkmarks for the foreground/back-
               ground/text/style filters. The checkmarks can be seen in the
               @{"Edit window" link WindowMenu}. Read the @{"General Information" link GeneralInfo} for information
               about the filters.

 @{b}Mouse paint@{ub} - @{u}Border@{uu}
               This allows you to draw textbased borders with your mouse.
               The bordercharacters used for drawing are taken from the
               active @{"keypadset" link WindowMenu}. This function is affected by the filters.

               @{u}Character@{uu}
               This one allows you to paint with your mouse. When selecting
               this function the user will be prompted to select a character,
               this is the character used for the painting. This function is
               affected by the filters.

               @{u}None@{uu}
               Turns off the mouse painting mode. The mouse can now be used
               for normal positioning of the cursor.

 @{b}Normal@{ub}      - Restores all editing-modes to normal. All style-functions
               will be cleared and all filters will be set. The mouse
               painting mode will also be turned off.

 @{b}Line »@{ub}
   @{b}Insert@{ub}   -  This will insert an empty line under the cursor. This
               function is not affected by the filters.

   @{b}Remove@{ub}   -  This will remove the line under the cursor. This function
               is not affected by the filters.

   @{b}Remove EOL@{ub}  -  This will remove everything on the row to the right of the
                  cursor (till the end of the line). Remove EOL can also be
                  reached by pressing SHIFT-DEL. This funtion is affected by
                  the filters.

   @{b}Remove BOL@{ub}  -  This will remove everything on the row to the left of the
                  cursor (till the beginning of the line). Remove BOL can
                  also be reached by pressing SHIFT-Backspace. This funtion
                  is affected by the filters.

 @{b}Column »@{ub}
   @{b}Insert@{ub}   -  This will insert an empty column at the cursor (removing
               column 80). This function is affected by the filters.

   @{b}Remove@{ub}   -  This will remove a column at the cursor (inserting an empty
               one at column 80). This function is affected by the filters.

 @{b}Flood fill@{ub}  - Fills the all characters with the same property that are
               connected with each other. If the Background-filter is on,
               flood fill will fill all the characters connected with each
               other that has the same background color. If only the
               Foreground-filter is turned on it will fill all characters
               connected with each other that has the same foreground color.

 @{b}ASCII insert...@{ub}
               Prompts the user to enter a specific ASCII-number. The
               ASCII-character entered will be inserted in the text just as
               if it was typed on the keyboard.

 @{b}ASCII table...@{ub}
               Prompts the user for a character. The character is chosen by
               selecting it with the mouse. It will be inserted in the text
               just as if it was typed on the keyboard.

 @{b}Show ASCII code...@{ub}
               Shows the user the ASCII code of the character underneath the
               cursor.

 @{b}Snap attribute@{ub}
               Snaps the attributes (style and color) from the character
               placed under the cursor. If you are lucky to have a mouse
               with three buttons, the middle button can also be used for
               snapping the attribute of the character underneath the cursor.

 @{b}Redraw screen@{ub}
               Redraws the current screen. (When typing in itallic the
               characters get cut. Use this function to redraw the screen
               and you will see how the final result will be.)
@endnode


@node WindowMenu "ANSI-Draw ... Menus - Window menu"

 @{u}Edit window@{uu}

 Will display/remove the edit window.
 The editwindow is used for selecting which attributes the text you type
 shall have. The filters (the checkmarks labeled "Foregr.","Backgr.","Text"
 and "Style") can also be turned on/off from this window as well as you can
 select in which editmode you want to be. The buttons "Snap attribute" and
 "Normal" are the same functions as under the @{"Edit menu" link EditMenu}.

 The edit window may freely be placed on the screen.


 @{u}Keypad window@{uu}

 Will display/remove the keypad window.
 The keypad on your keyboard has in this program been remaped. The keypad
 window shows the current keymap for the keypad. The user can choose between
 ten different keypadsets which can be redefined by the user. To change to
 the next keypadset just press the cyclegadget and the next set will be in
 use. If none of the predefined keysets suit you can you easily redefine
 them. Just press the gadget in the keypadwindow which represents the key
 you want to redefine and you will be prompted to select a new character.
 The ten different keypadsets are saved when saving the configuration.

 The current keypadset is also used when drawing borders. The keys 7,8,9,4,
 5,6,1,2,3,0 and . are used for that. Look at the default keyset 2,3,4 and 5
 to see how how to place your bordercharacters if you want to make your own
 borderset.

 The keypad window may freely be placed on the screen.

 @{u}Keyset@{uu}
 In this menu you can select a specific keyset without having to click
 through the keypad window.

@endnode


@node PreferencesMenu "ANSI-Draw ... Menus - Preferences menu"

 @{b}GUI...@{ub}
            This window allows the user to customize the userinterface.
            @{u}Mode cyclegadget@{uu}
            * PrivateScreen means that no other program can open windows
              on this program's screen.
            * PublicScreen allows the user to name this screen and place
              it in the list of public screens which allows other programs
              to open windows on this program's screen.
            * DefaultPublic means that this program snaps all the windows
              that wants to open on the default public screen (normally
              workbench) and opens them on this program's screen.

            @{u}Screenmode@{uu}
            Prompts the user to select in which screenmode the program will
            open its screen.

            @{u}Palette@{uu}
            Allows the user to define which palette to use. (If you for
            example want to use the workbench colors for editing)

            @{u}Font@{uu}
            Allows the user to select which font to use when editing.

            @{u}Pencolor cyclegadget@{uu}
            If you've made a palette that makes the userinterface in the
            program look like something the cat draged in, you can
            redefine the pens with which all the screens gadgets and windows
            are drawn with.

            @{u}Blank mouse@{uu}
            Removes the mousepointer while editing. Moving the mouse will
            display it again.

            @{u}ARexx requesters@{uu}
            If this flag is set, when ARexx determines a serious error it
            will display a requester.

            @{u}Initial rows@{uu}
            This is the number of empty rows to create when starting the
            program and when making a new project.

            @{u}# rows@{uu}
            This is the number of rows to be shown at the same time on the
            screen.

            @{u}Use@{uu}
            Select this if you accept all your GUI-settings made.

            @{u}Cancel@{uu}
            Select this to abort the GUI-settings made and restore your
            previous ones.

 @{b}File prefs...@{ub}
            In this window you define all that there is to be defined about
            the file handling.

            The "Load path" is the default path in the loadwindow when
            starting the program. The gadget after the "Load path"-
            stringgadget can be used to select a path by using a file-
            requester. The next stringgadget is the default load-extension
            and the next one is the default loadpattern.

            The same goes for "Save path" and "Backup path"

            @{u}End of line@{uu}
            This is how to handel the saving of lines. If CR is marked a
            Carrige return ($0d) is written and if LF is marked a Linefeed
            ($0a) is written at the end of lines. If both are marked the
            CR is saved before the LF.

            @{u}ANSI Init.@{uu}
            This is how to initialize the ANSI-output. If "Clear screen" is
            marked a clearscreen character will be written in the beginning
            of the file. If "Home cursor" is marked a command the places the
            cursor in the top left corner is saved (ESC-[0;0H). If "Reset"
            is marked an ANSI-reset is preformed in the beginning of the
            file (ESC-[0m).
            The "Prefix string" allows the user to define an own
            initializing sequence that shall be written in the beginning of
            the file. When loading a file, the "Prefix string" will not be
            loaded into the buffer.

            @{u}Create backups@{uu}
            Tells the program to save a backup of the old file when writing
            over one. The backup will be saved in the path defined by 
            "Backup path" with the extension that is placed beside
            "Backup path".

            @{u}Autosave@{uu}
            Tells the program to regularly save your current work.

            @{u}Minutes@{uu}
            This is the number of minutes to wait before autosaving.

            @{u}Ask@{uu}
            Tells the program to prompt the user before doing an autosave.

            @{u}Use@{uu}
            Select this if you accept all your file-settings made.

            @{u}Cancel@{uu}
            Select this to abort the file-settings made and restore your
            previous ones.

 @{b}Functionkeys...@{ub}
            In this program all the functionkeys can be mapped to represent
            a menu-selection.
            In this preferences window you can define your own functionskey
            mappings. To do an own mapping press one of the gadgets labeled
            'F1' to 'F10' or simply press the functionkey to remap. Now
            select which menuitem that functionkey should be mapped to in
            the menubar.

            If you are happy with your definitions made, press "Use"
            otherwise press "Cancel" to abort all changes made.

            This function is made for the ones of you how think that there
            are hotkeys missing for some of the menuitems or that the
            hotkeys are badly placed. 

 @{b}Toggle writemode...@{ub}
            This toggles the writemode between insert mode and overwrite
            mode. In overwrite mode no other characters but the one under
            the cursor will be modified or moved while typing.

 @{b}Load preferences...@{ub}
            This allows you to load preferences settings saved by the option
            "Save preferences..."
            (Only available in registered versions)

 @{b}Save preferences...@{ub}
            This allows you to save all your settings to a named file that
            can be loaded by using "Load preferences...".
            The settings saved are all preferences settings, edit and keypad
            window placements, if the edit or keypad windows are open and
            the ten different keypadsets defined.
            (Only available in registered versions)

 @{b}Save as default@{ub}
            Will save the preferences as default, which means that these
            are the preferences used when starting the program. The
            preferences file will be saved as "ENVARC:ANSI-draw.prefs".
            See "Save preferences..." to see which preferences that are
            saved.
            (Only available in registered versions)

 @{b}Load default@{ub}
            Will load the default preferences ("ENVARC:ANSI-draw.prefs")
            saved by "Save as default".
            (Only available in registered versions)

@endnode



@node Installation "ANSI-draw ... Installation"
Since you are already reading this  manual I suppose you've managed to
unpack the archive by yourself.  What you now have to do is to install
it. That is done by doubleclicking on the icon "HD-Install", this must
be done so  that the font and other stuff will be placed on it's right
places on your HD.

Here is a list of which files are placed where when installing:

file                       directory            description
-------------------------------------------------------
ANSI-Draw            -     ANSI-Draw/           Main program
ANSI-Draw.info       -     ANSI-Draw/           Icon
ANSI-Draw.guide      -     ANSI-Draw/           Manual
ANSI-Draw.guide.info -     ANSI-Draw/           Icon
Examples/            -     ANSI-Draw/           Examples directory
Examples.info        -     ANSI-Draw/           Icon
Prefs/               -     ANSI-Draw/           Preferences directory
ARexx/               -     ANSI-Draw/           ARexx directory
RegForm.txt          -     ANSI-Draw/           Registrationform
ANSIDraw_Logo1.ANSI  -     ANSI-Draw/Examples/  Example file
ANSIDraw_Logo2.ANSI  -     ANSI-Draw/Examples/  Example file
ANSIDraw_Logo3.ANSI  -     ANSI-Draw/Examples/  Example file
ANSIDraw_Logo4.ANSI  -     ANSI-Draw/Examples/  Example file
ColorChart.ANSI      -     ANSI-Draw/Examples/  Example file
HighlightBlock.rexx  -     ANSI-Draw/ARexx/     ARexx example file
Mandelbrot.rexx      -     ANSI-Draw/ARexx/     ARexx example file
UnlockInput.rexx     -     ANSI-Draw/ARexx/     ARexx example file
UnlockOutput.rexx    -     ANSI-Draw/ARexx/     ARexx example file
PC/                  -     FONTS:               PC font directory
PC.font              -     FONTS:               PC font
8                    -     FONTS:PC/            PC font

@endnode


@node Features "ANSI-Draw ... Features"

   Highlights:

   * Smart ANSI saving
   * Filtered editing of style,color and text changes
   * Mouse painting
   * Flood filling
   * Userdefinable keypadsets
   * Various blockcommands
   * Dynamic userinterface
   * Unlimited screenlength
   * ARexx-interface
@endnode


@node WhatToCome "ANSI-Draw ... What to come"

   Things to come in further versions:

   * Undo/Redo
   * Tidlecode window
   * Tabs
   * Goto line
   * Search/Replace
   * Import of IFF-pictures
   * Macros
   * More pages to edit on
   * Filter for ASCII-saving
   * Ruler

@endnode


@node Introduction "ANSI-Draw ... Introduction"

ANSI-Draw is an editor designed primary for editing standard ANSI screens.
By standard I mean that I've tried to follow the rules of ANSI-graphics as
much as possible. Not all ANSI-commands are yet supported but the most
important ones are. If you feel that you are missing anything don't hesitate
to contact me.

ANSI-Draw works fine for editing all sorts of textbased graphics for BBS
menus as well as layout for textbased PC-programs.

ANSI-Draw requires OS3.0 or higher.

I hope you will find this program usefull and I would appreciate hearing
your reactions on it.

Thanks.
@endnode


@node ProgramHistory "ANSI-Draw ... Program history"

List of what has happend to ANSI-Draw:

   v0.95    -  First pre-release.

   v0.96    -  * Fixed smarter ANSI-Saving by replacing the ANSI-command
                 ESC-[1D with ESC-[D.

               * Switching of Italic, Bold and Underline now refreshes the
                 keypad-window immeditely. (Sorry, but Reverse can't be
                 applied to the gadgets).

               * Delete EOL & Delete BOL implemented.

               * Requesters instead of just flashing screen, when error.

               * Quit-requester.

   v0.97    -  * Delete EOL/BOL/Line renamed to Remove EOL/BOL/Line.

               * Insert/Remove column in blocks implemented.

               * Insert/Remove column (on entire buffer) implemented.

               * Insert/Remove line in blocks implemented.

               * ARexx-interface implemented

               * Show ASCII code implemented
@endnode
